uments.getDescription()).isEqualTo(\\\\\\\"flyway-10\\\\\\\");\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    @Test\\\\n    void detectsAndLoadsConcreteImplementationClasses() throws Exception {\\\\n        ClassLoader classLoader = Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader();\\\\n\\\\n        assertThat(ClassUtils.isPresent(DefaultConstructed.class.getName(), classLoader)).isTrue();\\\\n        assertThat(ClassUtils.isImplementationPresent(TestService.class.getName(), classLoader)).isFalse();\\\\n\\\\n        Class<? extends TestService> loadedClass = ClassUtils.loadClass(\\\\n                TestService.class,\\\\n                TestServiceImplementation.class.getName(),\\\\n                classLoader);\\\\n\\\\n        assertThat(loadedClass).isEqualTo(TestServiceImplementation.class);\\\\n        assertThat(ClassUtils.loadClass(TestService.class, String.class.getName(), classLoader)).isNull();\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    @Test\\\\n    void readsStaticAndInstanceFieldValues() {\\\\n        assertThat(ClassUtils.getStaticFieldValue(\\\\n                FieldFixture.class.getName(),\\\\n                \\\\\\\"PUBLIC_STATIC_VALUE\\\\\\\",\\\\n                Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader()))\\\\n                .isEqualTo(\\\\\\\"static-value\\\\\\\");\\\\n        assertThat(ClassUtils.getFieldValue(new FieldFixture(), \\\\\\\"privateValue\\\\\\\"))\\\\n                .isEqualTo(\\\\\\\"instance-value\\\\\\\");\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    @Test\\\\n    void collectsValuesFromGettableMethods() {\\\\n        Map<String, String> values = ClassUtils.getGettableFieldValues(new GettableFixture(), \\\\\\\"flyway.\\\\\\\");\\\\n\\\\n        assertThat(values)\\\\n                .containsEntry(\\\\\\\"flyway.name\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"core\\\\\\\")\\\\n                .containsEntry(\\\\\\\"flyway.majorVersion\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"10\\\\\\\")\\\\n                .doesNotContainKey(\\\\\\\"flyway.secret\\\\\\\");\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    public static class DefaultConstructed {\\\\n        private final String value;\\\\n\\\\n        public DefaultConstructed() {\\\\n            this.value = \\\\\\\"default\\\\\\\";\\\\n        }\\\\n\\\\n        public String getValue() {\\\\n            return value;\\\\n        }\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    public static class ConstructedWithArguments {\\\\n        private final String description;\\\\n\\\\n        public ConstructedWithArguments(String name, Integer version) {\\\\n            this.description = name + \\\\\\\"-\\\\\\\" + version;\\\\n        }\\\\n\\\\n        public String getDescription() {\\\\n            return description;\\\\n        }\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    public interface TestService {\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    public static class TestServiceImplementation implements TestService {\\\\n        public TestServiceImplementation() {\\\\n        }\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    public static class FieldFixture {\\\\n        public static final String PUBLIC_STATIC_VALUE = \\\\\\\"static-value\\\\\\\";\\\\n\\\\n        private final String privateValue = \\\\\\\"instance-value\\\\\\\";\\\\n    }\\\\n\\\\n    public static class GettableFixture {\\\\n        public String getName() {\\\\n            return \\\\\\\"core\\\\\\\";\\\\n        }\\\\n\\\\n        public Integer getMajorVersion() {\\\\n            return 10;\\\\n        }\\\\n\\\\n        @DoNotMapForLogging\\\\n        public String getSecret() {\\\\n            return \\\\\\\"hidden\\\\\\\";\\\\n        }\\\\n    }\\\\n}\\\\n\\\"}\\n1334:[recv] {\\\"type\\\": \\\"message_end\\\", \\\"message\\\": {\\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"thinking\\\", \\\"thinking\\\": \\\"**Evaluating class instantiation in Java**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering the use of native image in Java with beans, and I wonder how Expression might use reflection on the class. It seems I need constructors registered by the agent. I notice that `instantiate(Class<T>)` deals with constructors effectively, whereas `loadClass` handles loading class names implementing interfaces. However, if a nested class has a `$` in its name, the corresponding filename does too. Should I stick to public top-level test classes, or can I use package-private non-public fixtures? It's a bit tricky!\\\\n\\\\n**Considering class accessibility in Java**\\\\n\\\\nI’m grappling with the distinction between top-level test classes and fixture classes. Generally, “all top-level test classes” refers to those containing tests, not fixtures. To avoid confusion with named inner dynamic classes, I think about using package-private top-level fixture classes in the same file. But I realize that `ClassUtils.loadClass` requires the constructor to be accessible. Since it calls `getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance` without `setAccessible`, the fixture class must be public with a public no-args constructor if it belongs to a different package.\\\\n\\\\n**Evaluating ClassUtils issue**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering a potential issue with ClassUtils.instantiate(String,...Object) that uses Expression with the method \\\\\\\"new.\\\\\\\" I think it might need to match the constructor exactly. I should look into how Java beans use Expression to target new class values with arguments since it can instantiate classes. For nested public static classes, I'll keep in mind that the constructor needs to be public. I might just need to use strings for constructor choices and asserts without directly using reflection.\\\\n\\\\n**Considering test classes**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether to write a new file or edit an existing one. If a top-level test class is package-private, it might violate the rule that states all top-level test classes must be public. The new file will be public, which is good. But what's the point of editing the existing one? I should think about keeping the placeholder, maybe making it public, but I definitely need to create the ClassUtilsTest file, since I'll ensure there's a mapping between report classes and test classes.\\\", \\\"thinkingSignature\\\